			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody">An interesting <a href="http://news.findlaw.com/hdocs/docs/scotus/mkbwarden62703cpet.pdf" target="_blank" class="postlink">case</a> came to my attention. It is a habeus corpus writ (basically: a court action that says the govt has to lawfully charge the person or let them go), that is now before the US Supreme Court. </span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Court records that were briefly public said the case is styled Mohamed Kamel Bellahouel v. Monica S. Wetzel. Wetzel is a former warden at the Federal Correctional Institution in South Miami-Dade County.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> In the Supreme Court docket, it is called MKB vs Warden.
<br />

<br />
What is rather chilling about this secret trial, is that MKB is out of jail on $10,000 bail (he is married to an American citizen). So it is obvious that this person is not likely to be charged with anything. Being out on bail like this tells me the person is most likely a material witness to something which is also secret.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>US Constitution wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Amendment VI
<br />

<br />
In all criminal prosecutions, the accused shall enjoy the right to a speedy and public trial, by an impartial jury of the state and district wherein the crime shall have been committed, which district shall have been previously ascertained by law, and to be informed of the nature and cause of the accusation; to be confronted with the witnesses against him; to have compulsory process for obtaining witnesses in his favor, and to have the assistance of counsel for his defense. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This trial, and others like it, are very <a href="http://www.volny.cz/ifolber/psaci/texty/kafka/trial.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">Kafkaesque</a>. Not only are you put on trial, you cannot be told what you are on trial for, nor can you (or your lawyer) be shown the evidence that will be used to convict you. And the most perverse thing about this trial, is that the whole trial is secret: preventing the public from calling <span style="font-style: italic">foul</span>.
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.law.com/jsp/article.jsp?id=1046833547729" target="_blank" class="postlink">law.com article</a>. 
<br />

<br />
For those of you who have not had the misfortune to visit it, Krome Detention Center in Miami-Dade county is a concentration camp that houses non-citizens. Some are refugees facing death if they are repatriated, some are people looking for a new life, some are crooks in any country they set foot in, but all are treated like dirt. Reports from there frequently tell of inmates being housed 48 to a room, with airconditioning nor toilets (outdoor temperatures in south Florida are over 90 for about 8 months per year, in buildings without a/c, temperatures rise to over 120). Inmates who file complaints get segregate into worse facilities (boxes without a/c, toilets, lights or windows). Public defenders who file complaints frequently get strip searched or denied entry as punative measures. Conditions so bad that the people there frequently agree to deportation rather that wait for trial.
<br />

<br />
So, the question is.... how many more secret trials are there?<span class="gensmall"></span>


				</div></td>
			</tr>
